          <strong>Director</strong>\r\n\r\n                Gian Yap\r\n                <em>Assistant Director</em>\r\n\r\n                Romano Alonzo\r\n                Zo Canaria\r\n                Arbie Dela Rosa\r\n                Mark Manguera\r\n                Lerizze Tan\r\n                Josh Siat\r\n                <em>Officers</em>\r\n            </td>\r\n            <td colspan="2" style="text-align: center">\r\n                Anna Monina Sanchez\r\n                <strong>Director</strong>\r\n\r\n                Cha Crisostomo\r\n                <em>Assistant Director</em>\r\n\r\n                Andee Aguila\r\n                Aileen Cu\r\n                Ayi Dave\r\n                Lisanne Gaborni\r\n                Henny Liao\r\n                Judith Pascual\r\n                Shelly Umali\r\n                <em>Officers</em>\r\n            </td>\r\n            <td colspan="2" style="text-align: center">\r\n                Sarah Elisha Ampil\r\n                <strong>Director</strong>\r\n\r\n                Chiara Buergo\r\n                <em>Assistant Director</em>\r\n\r\n                Ken Arcano\r\n                Justin Cabillos\r\n                Sel De Leon\r\n                Dana Dee\r\n                Magi Del Rosario\r\n                AK Mapolon\r\n                Klaud Moreno\r\n                Cyril Tablante\r\n                Jhett Yu\r\n                <em>Officers</em>\r\n            </td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n    </tbody>\r\n</table>	Organizers		inherit	open	open		19-revision-24			2013-06-19 17:10:01	2013-06-19 09:10:01		19	http://localhost/wordpress/19-revision-24/	0	revision		0
149	1	2013-06-19 17:21:07	2013-06-19 09:21:07	<p>NYC is an annual nationwide student-organized convention that aspires to provide high school students an engaging introduction to the field of economics, and to show the power of economic analysis and the economic way of thinking in clarifying relevant issues in society. As an event organized by the youth for the youth, NYC strives to provide an avenue where high school students from all over the country can learn about economic concepts and its applications, in a way that is easy to understand and highly relevant in the Philippine setting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The NYC is organized by the <a href="http://upecosoc.org/" target="_blank">UP Economics Society</a> and the <a href="http://fb.com/UPSE.StudentCouncil" target="_blank">UPSE Student Council</a>, two non-profit student organizations.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>History</h1>\r\n<p>In 2004, friends and aspiring student leaders Patti Camua and Len Punzalan were running for the UP Ecosoc Academic Affairs Committee Chairperson and the UPSE Student Council Education & Research Councilor, respectively. They joked that if they both win, they should join forces and organize an event together. True enough, they did, and the event that resulted was the National Youth Congress. (Read more about NYC’s founding <a href="http://echoes.ph/2011/09/27/a-congress-for-everyone/" target="_blank">here</a>.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the years, the Congress has grown into a deeply respected event, tackling pressing economic issues like labor migration, environmental sustainability and the country’s progress on the Millennium Development Goals. In 2008, it included among its speakers two notable senators— Edgardo Angara, who was the first post-Marcos UP President, and Noynoy Aquino, who would go on to become the President of the Philippines just two years later. Last year, the roster of speakers included household name Solita Collas-Monsod, better known as Winnie Monsod, the country’s National Economic Development Authority (NEDA) Director-General from 1986 to 1989.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was officially endorsed by the <a href="http://neda.gov.ph/about.asp" target="_blank">National Economic and Development Authority</a> for the first time in 2008 and by the <a href="http://deped.gov.ph/" target="_blank">Department of Education</a> in 2009. In 2010, the Congress expanded into a two-day event, with some delegates receiving accommodations at the University Hotel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last year, the NYC tackled the burgeoning field of Behavioral Economics, inviting speakers from both the economics and psychology disciplines. It was also preceded by <a href="http://fb.com/inkling.ph" target="_blank">Inkling</a>, a writing seminar/competition that featured an exclusive <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sUfDTywtQ3c" target="_blank">message</a> from reclusive author <a href="http://www.visprint.net/publications/bob/index.htm" target="_blank">Bob Ong</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Organizers</h1>\r\n<p>The <strong>UP Economics Society</strong> (UP Ecosoc) is a prominent student organization based in the University of the Philippines Diliman. Its founding in 1958 preceded the founding of its home college, the UP School of Economics, by eight years, which explains why its charter members are all from the College of Business Administration. Through its numerous and diverse activities, UP Ecosoc exhibits each of its three thrusts: <em>Service</em> in its outreach programs like medical missions and weekly daycare sessions, <em>Excellence</em> through its fundraising events like the <a href="http://www.facebook.com/upecosocmonth" target="_blank">Ecosoc Month parties</a>, <a href="http://www.facebook.com/musikapella" target="_blank">Musikapella</a>, and <a href="http://www.facebook.com/bandindemand" target="_blank">Band in Demand</a>, and <em>Tradition</em> through the shaping of its members into skilled, critical-minded individuals with a passion for using what they learn to give back to the country. The Society is centered around its Scholarship Fund, which, through the decades, have financially aided in the education of dozens of high school students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Visit the UP Ecosoc website at <a href="http://upecosoc.org/" target="_blank">upecosoc.org</a> or its <a href="http://www.facebook.com/up.economics.society" target="_blank">Facebook page</a> to find out more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The <strong>UP School of Economics Student Council</strong> (SESC) is one of the most eminent student councils in the University. Representing students taking up BS Economics and BS Business Economics, the SESC works to promote the discipline of economics across the campus. It achieves this through its annual Economics Week, its participation in the <a href="http://www.facebook.com/JSSCP" target="_blank">Junior Social Scientists’ Conference of the Philippines</a> (JSSCP), and the release of informative pamphlets, like one regarding the <a href="http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.228871173881530.37572.201782619923719&type=1" target="_blank">Oil Deregulation Law</a>. It also strives to maintain a camaraderie within the School of Economics by organizing bondings, sportsfests, and a varied wealth of other activities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Connect with the SESC by liking their <a href="http://www.facebook.com/UPSE.StudentCouncil" target="_blank">Facebook page</a>.</p>	About		inherit	open	open		4-revision-17			2013-06-19 17:21:07	2013-06-19 09:21:07		4	http://localhost/wordpress/4-revision-17/	0	revision		0
154	1	2013-06-21 12:36:39	2013-06-21 04:36:39	<p>Here are some common questions high schools ask regarding NYC. Need further clarifications? Don’t hesitate to email our External Relations team at <a href="mailto:er@nyc.org.ph" target="_blank">er@nyc.org.ph</a>!</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>How do we participate in NYC?</strong></h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n    <li>\r\n        Express your intention to join through:<ul>\r\n            <li>Text: 0917-536-3402</li>\r\n            <li>Email: <a href="mailto:er@nyc.org.ph" target="_blank">er@nyc.org.ph</a></li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n        Accomplish/submit the following requirements:<ul>\r\n            <li>Registration fee<span style="color: red">*</span></li>\r\n            <li>Participant's Form</li>\r\n            <li>Educator's Form</li>\r\n            <li>Scanned copy of deposit slip</li>\r\n        </ul\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>Requirements are due on or before <strong>August 9, 2013</strong></li>\r\n    <li>Send your student representatives with the accompanying faculty members to the designated vanue on <strong>August 30 and/or August 31</strong>.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="color: red">*</span><em>If you submit your requirements before <strong>August 9</strong>, you may avail of a special Php30 discount per delegate and a premium in the seating arrangements.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>How many delegates can we send?</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Each school may send a <strong>minimum of five (5)</strong> and a <strong>maximum of eight (8)</strong> participants for the congress and a <strong>maximum of two (2)</strong> members of the administration or faculty.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>What is the difference between the single day option and the overnight option?</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The congress proper takes place on the day of August 31, 2013. However, we understand that some of our participants will be coming from different regions and a single-day affair may not be worth the trip, so we offer an overnight option where the delegates will avail of hotel accommodations on the night of August 30.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To make the overnight option even more enticing, there will be a pre-event talk and dinner held exclusively for them. Transportation shall be provided from the hotel to the NYC venue for the following day, though schools may make their own transportation arrangements.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>My high school is not in Luzon. Can I still participate?</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Though the NYC to date has never had participants from outside Luzon due to the understandable logistical difficulties, we still maintain that our invitation extends to <em>all</em> DepEd-accredited high schools in the Philippines. We embrace challenges, so if you’re an interested school from Palawan, Visayas, or Mindanao, send us an email at <a href="mailto:er@nyc.org.ph" target="_blank">er@nyc.org.ph</a> and let’s work something out!</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Who will be responsible for the students during congress?</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The organizing body of the National Youth Congress - composed of students from the UP School of Economics Student Council and the UP Economics Society - shall be responsible for the students during the duration of the whole congress. On the other hand, the organizers are not responsible for the students in events outside the congress. Each delegate is required to submit a waiver stating the latter.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>What if we cannot stay for the full duration of NYC? Will there be a discount in the participation fee?</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>We regret to say that you will still be charged the full fee regardless of how much of the congress you attend.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>When is the deadline for confirming attendance?</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Deadline for confirmation is on or before <strong>August 9, 2013</strong>. If you pre-register and paythe entire amount of fees on or before <strong>August 9</strong>, you get a special discount of Php30 per delegate and a premium in the seating arrangement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For schools that confirm on or before <strong>July 31</strong> but opt not to pre-register, they will <em>not</em> have to pay the full fees yet. They are however required to submit a down payment worth 50% of the registration fee, plus an additional Php100 for overnight delegates. They will then have to pay the full amount by August 9.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please take not that late registrants and walk-ins shall be charged an extra fee.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>What do we need to bring?</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n    For those availing the overnight option:<ul>\r\n        <li>Clothes</li>\r\n        <li>Toiletries</li>\r\n        <li>Medication (if any)</li>\r\n        <li>Pocket money</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <br />\r\n    For everyone:<ul>\r\n        <li>School ID</li>\r\n        <li>Other personal necessities</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n</p>	FAQ		inherit	open	open		92-revision-10			2013-06-21 12:36:39	2013-06-21 04:36:39		92		0	revision		0
170	1	2013-06-24 23:34:35	2013-06-24 15:34:35	<p>These were the speakers of <a href="../../nyc-2012" target="_blank">NYC 2012</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<span>\r\n    <img src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Noel-del-Castillo.jpg" alt="Noel del Castillo" width="150" height="240" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-171" />\r\n    <h2 style="display: inline">Noel del Castillo</h2>\r\n</span>\r\n<p>Mr. del Castillo graduated from the UP Diliman School of Economics (UPSE) in 2006 and his Master of Arts in Economics in 2011. While doing his graduate studies, he was a teaching fellow at the UPSE, teaching several introductory economic theory classes in the undergraduate level. For a few years, he served as an analyst for the Philippine Stock Exchange. In 2010, he was one of the 25 participants in the Ronald Coase Institute Workshop held in Shanghai, an international workshop that gathers young economists and social scientists in formulating new institutional economic theory. There, he studied the importance of regulations such as the Securities Regulation Code in strengthening financial institutions like the stock market. Today, he serves as a lecturer in economics at Miriam College.</p>\r\n\r\n<span>\r\n    <img src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Solita-Monsod.jpg" alt="Solita Monsod" width="150" height="240" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-173" />\r\n    <h2 style="display: inline">Solita Collas-Monsod</h2>\r\n    <em>Download</em>: <a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Solita-Monsod-MDGs-Made-Easy.ppt">Solita Monsod - MDG's Made Easy</a>\r\n</span>\r\n<p>Mrs. Monsod, popularly known as “Mareng Winnie," is an academician, media personality, public servant, and deemed one of the top economists of the country. She obtained her Bachelor of Science in Economics at the UPSE, graduating cum laude, and her Master of the Arts and Ph.D. in Economics at the University of Pensylvania, completing all her requirements for the latter except her dissertation. She began teaching at the UPSE in 1971 and is today a professor emerita. Specializing in development economics, she has worked extensively in government, serving as National Economic Development Advisory (NEDA) Director-General from 1986-1989 and at various agencies of the United Nations. Mrs. Monsod is probably best known for her television shows, which include <em>Bawal ang Pasaway</em> and <em>Unang Hirit</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<span>\r\n    <img src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Benjamin-Diokno.jpg" alt="Benjamin Diokno" width="150" height="240" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-176" />\r\n    <h2 style="display: inline">Benjamin E. Diokno</h2>\r\n    <em>Download</em>: <a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Benjamin-Diokno-Where-Do-We-Go-From-Here.ppt">Benjamin Diokno - Where Do We Go From Here</a>\r\n</span>\r\n<p>Dr. Diokno graduated with a BA in Public Administration as his undergraduate degree and an MA in Public Administration as his masteral degree. After receiving a Certificate in Developmental Economics in the UPSE under a University of Wisconsin program, he continued his pursuit of economics by obtaining graduate degrees in Economics from the UPSE and in Political Economy at Johns Hopkins University, as well as a Ph.D. in Economics from Syracuse University in New York. Dr. Diokno served as Budget Secretary from 1998-2001 and has worked with the Asian Development Bank (ADB), the European Commission, the United States Agency for International Development (USAID), and the government of Cambodia. Besides teaching, he is a columnist for <em>Business World</em> and <em>Malaya Business Insight</em>.</p>	Speakers		inherit	open	open		125-autosave			2013-06-24 23:34:35	2013-06-24 15:34:35		125	http://localhost/wordpress/125-autosave/	0	revision		0
