285	2	2013-07-08 06:20:47	2013-07-07 22:20:47	<p>NYC is an annual nationwide student-organized convention that aspires to provide high school students an engaging introduction to the field of economics, and to show the power of economic analysis and the economic way of thinking in clarifying relevant issues in society. As an event organized by the youth for the youth, NYC strives to provide an avenue where high school students from all over the country can learn about economic concepts and its applications, in a way that is easy to understand and highly relevant in the Philippine setting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The NYC is organized by the <a href="http://upecosoc.org/" target="_blank">UP Economics Society</a> and the <a href="http://fb.com/UPSE.StudentCouncil" target="_blank">UPSE Student Council</a>, two non-profit student organizations.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>History</h1>\r\n<table>\r\n    <tbody>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td width="33%">\r\n                <img src="http://106.186.21.135/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/NYC-7-Poster.jpg" alt="NYC 7 Poster" width="100%" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-160" />\r\n            </td>\r\n            <td width="33%">\r\n                <img src="http://106.186.21.135/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/NYC-8-Poster.jpg" alt="NYC 8 Poster" width="100%" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-161" />\r\n            </td>\r\n            <td width="33%">\r\n                <img src="http://106.186.21.135/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/NYC-9-Poster.jpg" alt="NYC 9 Poster" width="100%" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-162" />\r\n            </td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td style="text-align: center">NYC 7 Poster</td>\r\n            <td style="text-align: center">NYC 8 Poster</td>\r\n            <td style="text-align: center">NYC 9 Poster</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n    </tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>In 2004, friends and aspiring student leaders Patti Camua and Len Punzalan were running for the UP Ecosoc Academic Affairs Committee Chairperson and the UPSE Student Council Education & Research Councilor, respectively. They joked that if they both win, they should join forces and organize an event together. True enough, they did, and the event that resulted was the National Youth Congress. (Read more about NYC’s founding <a href="http://echoes.ph/2011/09/27/a-congress-for-everyone/" target="_blank">here</a>.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the years, the Congress has grown into a deeply respected event, tackling pressing economic issues like labor migration, environmental sustainability and the country’s progress on the Millennium Development Goals. In 2008, it included among its speakers two notable senators— Edgardo Angara, who was the first post-Marcos UP President, and Noynoy Aquino, who would go on to become the President of the Philippines just two years later. Last year, the roster of speakers included household name Solita Collas-Monsod, better known as Winnie Monsod, the country’s National Economic Development Authority (NEDA) Director-General from 1986 to 1989.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was officially endorsed by the <a href="http://neda.gov.ph/about.asp" target="_blank">National Economic and Development Authority</a> for the first time in 2008 and by the <a href="http://deped.gov.ph/" target="_blank">Department of Education</a> in 2009. In 2010, the Congress expanded into a two-day event, with some delegates receiving accommodations at the University Hotel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last year, the NYC tackled the burgeoning field of Behavioral Economics, inviting speakers from both the economics and psychology disciplines. It was also preceded by <a href="http://fb.com/inkling.ph" target="_blank">Inkling</a>, a writing seminar/competition that featured an exclusive <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sUfDTywtQ3c" target="_blank">message</a> from reclusive author <a href="http://www.visprint.net/publications/bob/index.htm" target="_blank">Bob Ong</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Organizers</h1>\r\n<p><img src="http://106.186.21.135/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/EcoSoc-Logo.png" alt="EcoSoc Logo" width="150" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-163" />The <strong>UP Economics Society</strong> (UP Ecosoc) is a prominent student organization based in the University of the Philippines Diliman. Its founding in 1958 preceded the founding of its home college, the UP School of Economics, by eight years, which explains why its charter members are all from the College of Business Administration. Through its numerous and diverse activities, UP Ecosoc exhibits each of its three thrusts: <em>Service</em> in its outreach programs like medical missions and weekly daycare sessions, <em>Excellence</em> through its fundraising events like the <a href="http://www.facebook.com/upecosocmonth" target="_blank">Ecosoc Month parties</a>, <a href="http://www.facebook.com/musikapella" target="_blank">Musikapella</a>, and <a href="http://www.facebook.com/bandindemand" target="_blank">Band in Demand</a>, and <em>Tradition</em> through the shaping of its members into skilled, critical-minded individuals with a passion for using what they learn to give back to the country. The Society is centered around its Scholarship Fund, which, through the decades, have financially aided in the education of dozens of high school students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Visit the UP Ecosoc website at <a href="http://upecosoc.org/" target="_blank">upecosoc.org</a> or its <a href="http://www.facebook.com/up.economics.society" target="_blank">Facebook page</a> to find out more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src="http://106.186.21.135/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/SESC.png" alt="SESC" width="150" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-164" />The <strong>UP School of Economics Student Council</strong> (SESC) is one of the most eminent student councils in the University. Representing students taking up BS Economics and BS Business Economics, the SESC works to promote the discipline of economics across the campus. It achieves this through its annual Economics Week, its participation in the <a href="http://www.facebook.com/JSSCP" target="_blank">Junior Social Scientists’ Conference of the Philippines</a> (JSSCP), and the release of informative pamphlets, like one regarding the <a href="http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.228871173881530.37572.201782619923719&type=1" target="_blank">Oil Deregulation Law</a>. It also strives to maintain a camaraderie within the School of Economics by organizing bondings, sportsfests, and a varied wealth of other activities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Connect with the SESC by liking their <a href="http://www.facebook.com/UPSE.StudentCouncil" target="_blank">Facebook page</a>.</p>	About		inherit	open	open		4-revision-28			2013-07-08 06:20:47	2013-07-07 22:20:47		4	http://nyc.org.ph/4-revision-28/	0	revision		0
